  "diagnosis": {
    "q4_dual": "Q4 dual dominates selected MoE. Retained 32x16 halves col-grid blocks (2048->1024 grid_x) and beats legacy 16x16 by ~6.0 ms despite higher VGPR (trace 72 vs 56; code num_vgpr 65 vs 51). It still reloads/dequantizes raw Q4_K scale/min and quant bytes for every WMMA row tile; executed-tile weight footprint estimate is ~107 GB and activation reload envelope is ~194 GB for 40 layers, far above unique active expert weight footprint (~10 GB). Bottleneck is inner-loop raw GGUF-K decode + repeated weight/activation work, not scheduler metadata or stores.",
    "q5_down": "Q5 down is second largest. Legacy 16x16 has trace VGPR 64/code num_vgpr 64 and no scratch/LDS. Generic multi-tile variants increase code-object VGPR to 76-139 and were slower. Throughput is similar TFLOP/s to Q4, indicating WMMA math is busy but dequant/activation reload prevents enough gain from bigger tiles.",
    "q6_down": "Q6 down is small (~2.8 ms) and not worth first attack except if Q5 design generalizes cheaply.",
    "pmc": "Hardware counter collection was not usable beyond SQ_WAVES on this setup; trace metadata gives static occupancy/register evidence."
  },
  "ranked_plan": [
    {
      "rank": 1,
      "item": "Prototype hot-expert Q4 dual kernel that keeps 32x16 block count reduction but reduces per-tile raw Q4 scale/min decode/register pressure. First target: Q4 dual <=45 ms replay, then <=40 ms full rocprof. Candidate: predecode Q4_K scale/min sidecar for active hot experts or split scale/min decode into sidecar while retaining raw q nibbles."
    },
    {
      "rank": 2,
      "item": "Avoid increasing VGPR above retained Q4 32x16. Q4 64x16/64x32 code-object num_vgpr 105/128 and Q5 64x* 131/139 explain prior slowdowns. New hot kernel should keep trace VGPR <=72 and no scratch."
    },
